    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nLooking at the reaction SMIRKS:\nCC[O:21][C:20]1(CN(CC2=C(N1)C=CC(=C2)Cl)C(=O)OC(C)(C)C)[O-:10] >> CC[O-:21].CC(C)(C)OC(=O)N1CC2=C(C=CC(=C2)Cl)N[C:20](=[O:10])C1\n\nLet me trace the mapped atoms:\n\nReactant: CC[O:21][C:20]1(CN(CC2=C(N1)C=CC(=C2)Cl)C(=O)OC(C)(C)C)[O-:10]\n\nProducts: CC[O-:21] and CC(C)(C)OC(=O)N1CC2=C(C=CC(=C2)Cl)N[C:20](=[O:10])C1\n\nKey observations:\n\n1. Atom 21 (O): In reactant, it's part of CCO:21 group (ethoxy oxygen bonded to C:20). In product, it becomes CC[O-:21] (ethoxide anion). So the O:21-C:20 bond is broken.\n\n2. Atom 10 (O): In reactant, it's [O-:10] bonded to C:20 (as part of a peroxy/hemiacetal-like structure where C:20 has both O:21 and O-:10). In product, it becomes C:20(=[O:10]) - a carbonyl oxygen double-bonded to C:20.\n\nSo the reaction center involves:\n- Breaking of the O:21-C:20 bond (ethoxy group leaves as ethoxide)\n- Conversion of C:20-O-:10 single bond to C:20=O:10 double bond (carbonyl formation)\n\nThis is essentially a fragmentation where the C:20 center loses the ethoxy group and the lone pair on O-:10 forms a double bond with C:20, creating a carbonyl (lactam). This is a retro-hetero-ene type fragmentation or more specifically, a N-O bond cleavage with carbonyl formation.\n\nWait, let me look more carefully at the structure. The reactant has C:20 bonded to O:21 (ethoxy) and O-:10 (oxide), and it's part of a ring (the 1 indicates ring closure). The ring includes N1. So C:20 is part of a cyclic structure where it's bonded to both oxygens and nitrogen.\n\nIn the product, C:20 is now a carbonyl carbon (C:20=O:10) in a lactam ring, and the ethoxy group has left as ethoxide.\n\nThe reaction center is:\n- Bond broken: O:21-C:20\n- Bond changed: C:20-O:10 from single to double bond\n\nThis is a fragmentation/elimination reaction where an N,O-acetal (or hemiaminal ether) fragments to give a lactam and ethoxide.\n\nThe reaction center in terms of bond edits:\n1. Break O:21-C:20 bond\n2. Change C:20-O:10 from single to double bond\n\nLet me format this as a reaction edit summary."
